hange Section 230 as currently interpreted). This bit stood out to me:

Some justices raised the obvious but necessary question here in a case that=
 comes down to how a statute ought to be interpreted =E2=80=94 shouldn=E2=
=80=99t all this be left to Congress? Particularly when removing these liab=
ility protections seems certain to trigger a wave of litigation?

I agree with Newton that this is the right question; it=E2=80=99s fair to a=
rgue that the current regulatory environment is not perfect. At the same ti=
me, it should be acknowledged that it has worked pretty well ( https://stra=
techery.com/2022/free-netflix-follow-up-the-senate-tech-bill/?access_token=
=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5=
cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidX=
