On to the update:

Diamond Sports Misses Interest Payment
--------------------------------------

From the New York Times ( https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/15/sports/diamond=
-sports-debt-interest.html ) :

Diamond Sports Group, which owns and operates 19 regional sports networks t=
hat televise about a third of all M.L.B., N.B.A. and N.H.L. games, said on =
Wednesday that it would not make a $140 million interest payment on its nea=
rly $9 billion of debt, setting the stage for a possible bankruptcy filing =
next month and building pressure for the leagues and others amid a sea chan=
ge in how fans watch sports throughout the United States. The missed paymen=
t triggered a 30-day grace period, and Diamond Sports said on Wednesday tha=
t it intended to keep talking with the leagues and its creditors to come up=
 with more favorable arrangements to televise games during that time.

The sports networks, which are branded Bally Sports and include channels li=
ke Bally Sports Florida and Bally Sports San Diego, exist mainly because Di=
amond Sports pays hefty fees to teams for the rights to show their games lo=
cally, and cable customers pay fees in their cable bills that keep the chan=
nels afloat. The company owes teams about $2 billion in rights fees this ye=
ar, according to its most recent financial filing, and the fees have contin=
ued to increase even as fewer Americans stick with cable television, meanin=
g less revenue for Diamond Sports.

This bankruptcy has been coming for a while; I explained the problems Diamo=
nd Sports was facing in this 2021 Daily Update ( https://stratechery.com/20=
21/mlb-versus-sinclair-what-happened-to-sinclair-the-problem-for-sports-lea=
gues/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3=
J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxp=
bmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidXJpIjpbImh0dHBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hlcnkuY29tLzIwMjEvbWxiLXZlcnN=
1cy1zaW5jbGFpci13aGF0LWhhcHBlbmVkLXRvLXNpbmNsYWlyLXRoZS1wcm9ibGVtLWZvci1zcG=
9ydHMtbGVhZ3Vlcy8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTY3OTY2MDYzMCwiaWF0IjoxNjc3MDY4NjMwLCJpc3MiO=
iJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVl=
ZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V=
1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXNlIjoiYWNjZXNzIn0.qHo82ehwAc_t6LPKD7YaL0edi1=
6o9_PWQ0gjDclHhhEbRqzZCvNgL0MirPmilA3T9ZsNbcY8Jgn_YOvqtyO6EmR7pl_2QjSnKv_7A=
D88eusO-qaYhqByCI6TmNkiZlEx2-TITtGYLyIasnp9-xemkxYd6A8yIQUmH87nrVa81iFbtDLs=
g6XWaNAaRBrKwQ7yMqreivzmyxkRC-5wGVMaI1r-w2n0sk6KSsGU9Tm9Lv6uJZljQxI810XmJO4=
njTMvfFpkvcIHehg5ZclIGus5bA1yFyDBWcPzQSFCYfAGmPtLAhhnBQ1XnqHPh9WmScQ_yO7w5u=
wtlS3iVx5bnPyjMA ). To summarize:

* Baseball (MLB), basketball (NBA), and hockey (NHL) sell national rights t=
o national networks, and local rights to regional sports networks; both nat=
ional networks and regional sports networks monetize through a combination =
of advertising and carriage fees. The latter are particularly important bec=
ause everyone who subscribes to a cable bundle pays those fees, which means=
 that non-sports fans are effectively subsidizing sports fans.
* Cord-cutting accelerated over the last several years, reducing the number=
 of people paying carriage fees.
* Virtual bundles like YouTube TV excluded RSNs, judging that the small num=
ber of people who wanted access to every game were not worth the customer a=
cquisition benefits of being able to charge a meaningfully lower price for =
their bundle relative to cable (given that RSNs have the highest carriage f=
ees this side of ESPN).

This dynamic, in conjunction with the pandemic, was disastrous for Diamond =
Sports, which was set up as an independent subsidiary of Sinclair Broadcast=
 Group, which acquired the RSNs from Disney as a condition of the latter=E2=
=80=99s acquisition of 21st Century Fox. In fact, it=E2=80=99s difficult to=
 overstate just how disastrous things have gone.

Bally=E2=80=99s Dire Situation
----------------------

The problem for Diamond Sports is not simply the fact that they have massiv=
e interest payments; the company has also failed to make an annual operatin=
g profit =E2=80=94 i.e. a profit before interest payments =E2=80=94 since 2=
019. Some of those losses, to be fair, were due to impairment charges, but =
those impairment charges were themselves functions of lost distribution dea=
ls and changes in the evaluation of the value of sports rights going forwar=
d. In short, this is a business that, at least in the case of the Bally Spo=
rts Networks, just doesn=E2=80=99t work.

I have an admission to make: I went into this analysis assuming that the pr=
imary problem for Diamond Sports was their debt load; surely RSN=E2=80=99s =
were still profitable on an operating basis, but $8 billion in debt was sim=
ply too much given the declining revenue resulting from cord-cutting and be=
ing cut out from virtual bundles. In fact, though, the situation has deteri=
orated even more than I realized: Diamond would not be bankrupt without the=
 debt, but they would not be making money either (and operating cash flow, =
even if you want to ignore the impairment charges, has been negative for ov=
er a year).

It=E2=80=99s difficult to ascertain if this is a Diamond-only problem: the =
second biggest set of RSNs are owned by Comcast, and their results are fold=
ed in with the NBCUniversal=E2=80=99s results. Comcast=E2=80=99s RSNs are a=
lso negotiating with, well, Comcast for carriage fees; in any dying industr=
y consolidation is the best way to keep the ship afloat for a while longer,=
 and Comcast is already there.

Bally channels, on the other hand, are individual boats adrift in a hurrica=
ne: as I noted in that previous Daily Update, they aren=E2=80=99t linked to=
 other cable channels as they were when they were owned by Fox, which gives=
 them a much weaker bargaining position with distributors; they=E2=80=99re =
also not integrated with distributors or teams, which means whatever gross =
profit they can wring out =E2=80=94 and they still made $348 million in gro=
ss profits through the first nine months of last year (the company hasn=E2=
=80=99t released its annual report yet) =E2=80=94 have to be extracted from=
 either teams or distributors.

The question is just how much bankruptcy can improve the situation.

Negotiating Bankruptcy
----------------------

Back to the Article:

For months, Diamond Sports, which reported $585 million cash on hand in its=
 latest financial filing, has been discussing its bleak outlook with Sincla=
ir, its creditors and the sports leagues. But the missed payment starts a 3=
0-day timer to craft an acceptable deal before Diamond Sports could default=
 on its debt. All the parties have been broadly negotiating a deal in which=
 Diamond Sports would enter Chapter 11 bankruptcy with a reorganization pla=
n, according to two people involved in the negotiations. The people spoke o=
n condition of anonymity because they were not authorized to speak publicly=
 about the negotiations.

Although no deal has been made, the people said the companies had been nego=
tiating a bankruptcy in which Sinclair would give up most of its ownership =
stake in Diamond Sports, while creditors would take the equity in exchange =
for restructuring or forgiving up to $8 billion of its debts. Sports league=
s would grant additional rights to Diamond Sports, particularly digital rig=
hts, to help put the regional sports network on stronger footing to seek mo=
re loans or a sale.

But the terms of any agreement could shift substantially, and there is no g=
uarantee there will be one at all. If most of the involved parties are unab=
le to come to an agreement, Diamond Sports would most likely file for a fre=
e-fall bankruptcy, in which the bankruptcy court would play a much larger r=
ole and the leagues and the creditors would be in greater danger of not bei=
ng paid at all.

That last sentence gets at why the dynamics around this bankruptcy are so i=
nteresting:

* Money comes from cable bundle subscribers, who pay the cable company, whi=
ch pays the RSN.
* Teams get money from the RSN for the rights to their games.
* Leftover money is used to pay creditors.

At first blush it makes sense that creditors would, in lieu of going to ban=
kruptcy court, simply receive the RSNs as collateral. The problem, though, =
is that the RSNs appear to be worthless! Note this story from ESPN ( https:=
//www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/35668388/rob-manfred-mlb-ready-diamond-sports=
-group-pay-teams ) about baseball, which will feel the pain first given tha=
t its season is about to kick off:

Diamond Sports Group=E2=80=99s unraveling could open an opportunity for MLB=
 to take control of all its rights and potentially end blackouts once and f=
or all, which has long been a central focus for the league. But going direc=
t-to-consumer would not allow MLB to match the money it currently generates=
 through the cable model. =E2=80=9CNot in the short term,=E2=80=9D Manfred =
said.

It could, however, be a short-term fix while the dust settles on Diamond Sp=
orts Group=E2=80=99s restructuring. If the company misses any payments to t=
eams, those teams will have the option to terminate their contracts, [Commi=
ssioner Rob] Manfred said.

=E2=80=9CIn the event that MLB stepped in, what we would do is we would pro=
duce the games,=E2=80=9D Manfred said. =E2=80=9CWe would make use of our as=
set, the MLB Network, to do that. We would go directly to distributors =E2=
=80=94 meaning Comcast, Charter, the big distributors =E2=80=94 and make an=
 agreement to have those games distributed on cable networks. My expectatio=
ns is that as part of the negotiation, there would be a negotiation over pr=
ice. And that probably gets back to the question about, you know, what the =
economics would look like, but we would also be seeking flexibility on the =
digital side.=E2=80=9D

This gets at the problem for creditors: RSNs are only valuable to the exten=
t that they have rights to the local team. If the RSNs miss a payment, thou=
gh, Manfred claims that those contracts can be terminated, which makes the =
RSN worthless to a cable distributor; to make the payment, though, means mi=
nimal cash left over for creditors.

At the same time, it=E2=80=99s not as if teams are in the clear for the exa=
ct reason Manfred acknowledged; RSNs, even in their wounded state, drive fa=
r more revenue than any team =E2=80=94 or MLB as a whole =E2=80=94 could ma=
ke by selling games directly: even with the diminished cable customer base =
it still makes more sense to charge every cable subscriber for MLB than to =
charge diehard fans directly, above and beyond the importance of having a w=
ay to acquire new customers. This is why it is likely that creditors and te=
ams will make a deal: everyone is motivated to keep the old model in place =
for now.

Here is what I think a deal might look like. First, as the ESPN article not=
es, leagues would prefer to be able to sell streaming packages to local fan=
s, but have not in the past because RSNs paid a premium to have exclusive r=
ights. It makes sense for the leagues to make abandoning this exclusivity a=
 condition of reducing their rights fees. Creditors, meanwhile, simply want=
 to get their money back, and aren=E2=80=99t worried about the long-term: r=
educing rights fees is one way to cut costs; another way would be to hand o=
ff production to the teams/leagues. That, though, might actually be attract=
ive to the leagues, given they want to unify the streaming rights.

The big question for everyone involved is what might the end of exclusivity=
 mean for those who still subscribe to the cable bundle, and for Bally in p=
articular. Why wouldn=E2=80=99t Comcast or Spectrum or other cable operator=
s respond to RSNs no longer having exclusive rights to sports by cutting th=
em out of the bundle, and becoming price competitive with virtual bundles? =
Perhaps the calculation is that the cable bundle is like print newspapers 1=
5 years ago: the only remaining subscribers aren=E2=80=99t going anywhere, =
at least until they die.

What does seem prudent, at least in the long run, is for leagues to priorit=
ize their national TV deals; I think an important consideration here, for b=
asketball anyways, ought to be fewer games, enhancing the value of those th=
at are nationally televised. This would be easier to accomplish if RSN mone=
y is off the table (then teams are only forgoing additional gate and conces=
sions revenue); I hope the NBA in particular seizes the opportunity.

